SIMPLE: stultify
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stultify
<hw>Stul"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stultified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stultifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>stultus</ets> foolish + <ets>-fy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
make foolish; to make a fool of; <as>as, to <ex>stultify</ex> one by
imposition; to <ex>stultify</ex> one's self by silly reasoning or
conduct</as>.</def> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To regard as a fool, or as foolish.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The modern sciolist <qex>stultifies</qex> all understanding but
his own, and that which he conceives like his own.</q>
<rj><au>Hazlitt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To allege or prove to be of unsound
mind, so that the performance of some act may be avoided.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stultiloquence</ent>⟦br⟧
